1
00:00:00,120 --> 00:00:04,720
Imagine for a second that you wake up tomorrow and the ATM doesn't work.

2
00:00:04,720 --> 00:00:07,360
You go to the bank and the doors are locked.

3
00:00:07,360 --> 00:00:13,600
You check your phone and the news says the United States government has run out of money.

4
00:00:13,600 --> 00:00:15,120
Not budget cuts money.

5
00:00:15,120 --> 00:00:18,720
I mean zero.

6
00:00:18,720 --> 00:00:20,000
Empty pockets.

7
00:00:20,000 --> 00:00:21,840
There is no Federal Reserve.

8
00:00:21,840 --> 00:00:23,640
There is no stimulus check.

9
00:00:23,640 --> 00:00:25,200
There is no plan.

10
00:00:25,200 --> 00:00:32,060
This sounds like the plot of a post-apocalyptic movie, but in 1907 this was real life.

11
00:00:32,060 --> 00:00:37,440
The entire American economy was a house of cards and someone had just bumped the table.

12
00:00:37,440 --> 00:00:42,340
As the country prepared to slide into a second Great Depression, the government didn't step

13
00:00:42,340 --> 00:00:44,120
in to save the day.

14
00:00:44,120 --> 00:00:45,120
They couldn't.

15
00:00:45,120 --> 00:00:51,720
Instead, the fate of every single American's bank account rested in the hands of one man.

16
00:00:51,720 --> 00:00:57,460
A man with a massive mustache, a terrifying temper, and more power than the president.

17
00:00:57,460 --> 00:01:03,040
His name was J.P. Morgan and he was about to pull off the most legendary high-stakes boss

18
00:01:03,040 --> 00:01:06,140
move in the history of capitalism.

19
00:01:06,140 --> 00:01:10,820
But before we get to the secret library and the locked doors, we have to understand how

20
00:01:10,820 --> 00:01:17,060
a couple of greedy guys tried to cheat the system and accidentally set the world on fire.

21
00:01:17,060 --> 00:01:21,380
To understand 1907, you have to understand trusts.

22
00:01:21,380 --> 00:01:24,760
Think of a trust like a VIP snack club.

23
00:01:24,760 --> 00:01:27,480
In a normal bank, there are strict rules.

24
00:01:27,480 --> 00:01:31,920
You put your money in, the bank keeps some, and they lend some out.

25
00:01:31,920 --> 00:01:36,240
But a trust was like the cool, rebellious younger brother of a bank.

26
00:01:36,240 --> 00:01:42,300
They had fewer rules, they took bigger risks, and they promised way higher returns.

27
00:01:42,300 --> 00:01:46,360
By 1907, these trusts were booming.

28
00:01:46,360 --> 00:01:52,360
Everyone was pouring their life savings into them because, hey, more money is better, right?

29
00:01:52,360 --> 00:01:54,660
Well here is the first twist.

30
00:01:54,660 --> 00:01:58,600
The biggest financial crisis in history didn't start with a bank.

31
00:01:58,600 --> 00:02:00,460
It started with copper.

32
00:02:00,460 --> 00:02:02,300
Meet Augustus Heinze.

33
00:02:02,300 --> 00:02:06,460
He was a wealthy guy who thought he was the smartest person in the room.

34
00:02:06,460 --> 00:02:09,820
He hatched a plan to corner the copper market.

35
00:02:09,820 --> 00:02:12,760
Imagine there are only 100 apples in the world.

36
00:02:12,760 --> 00:02:17,720
If you buy 99 of them, you can charge whatever you want for that last apple.

37
00:02:17,720 --> 00:02:19,560
That was Heinze's plan.

38
00:02:19,560 --> 00:02:21,040
But with copper.

39
00:02:21,040 --> 00:02:26,340
He borrowed millions of dollars from a bank, the Mercantile National Bank, to buy up every

40
00:02:26,340 --> 00:02:28,480
share of a copper company.

41
00:02:28,480 --> 00:02:32,720
He thought he could force everyone else to buy from him at a massive price.

42
00:02:32,720 --> 00:02:34,640
But he messed up the math.

43
00:02:34,640 --> 00:02:36,980
The plan failed spectacularly.

44
00:02:36,980 --> 00:02:38,940
The stock price didn't go up.

45
00:02:38,940 --> 00:02:41,740
It teleported to zero.

46
00:02:41,740 --> 00:02:43,220
Heinze was ruined.

47
00:02:43,220 --> 00:02:44,960
But here's the problem.

48
00:02:44,960 --> 00:02:48,780
Because Heinze had used the bank's money to gamble, the public realized the bank was

49
00:02:48,780 --> 00:02:50,280
now empty.

50
00:02:50,280 --> 00:02:52,320
People didn't just walk to the bank.

51
00:02:52,320 --> 00:02:53,560
They ran.

52
00:02:53,560 --> 00:02:56,600
This is what we call a bank run.

53
00:02:56,600 --> 00:03:01,800
Imagine you and all your friends realize the snack club leader ate all the cookies.

54
00:03:01,800 --> 00:03:04,740
You all show up at once demanding your cookies back.

55
00:03:04,740 --> 00:03:06,800
But the cookies are gone.

56
00:03:06,800 --> 00:03:09,640
The Mercantile National Bank collapsed.

57
00:03:09,640 --> 00:03:12,180
And that was just the first domino.

58
00:03:12,180 --> 00:03:19,520
You see, in 1907, all these banks and trusts were interconnected like a giant spider web.

59
00:03:19,520 --> 00:03:26,460
When the Mercantile fell, people started looking at the other snack clubs and wondering, wait,

60
00:03:26,460 --> 00:03:27,960
is my money safe?

61
00:03:27,960 --> 00:03:32,720
The eyes of the public turned toward the biggest, most prestigious club in town.

62
00:03:32,720 --> 00:03:34,680
The Knickerbocker Trust.

63
00:03:34,680 --> 00:03:37,220
It was the gold standard of trusts.

64
00:03:37,220 --> 00:03:40,900
If the Knickerbocker was okay, everyone was okay.

65
00:03:40,900 --> 00:03:45,280
But the president of the Knickerbocker had been seen hanging out with Heinze, the copper

66
00:03:45,280 --> 00:03:46,980
guy.

67
00:03:46,980 --> 00:03:48,700
That was all it took.

68
00:03:48,700 --> 00:03:50,300
One rumor.

69
00:03:50,300 --> 00:03:51,460
One spark.

70
00:03:51,460 --> 00:03:56,200
On Tuesday morning, a line of people stretched around the block of the Knickerbocker.

71
00:03:56,200 --> 00:03:58,720
They weren't there to deposit money.

72
00:03:58,720 --> 00:04:00,600
They were there to get out.

73
00:04:00,600 --> 00:04:05,980
In less than three hours, the Knickerbocker paid out $8 million in cash.

74
00:04:05,980 --> 00:04:07,700
Then the vaults went dry.

75
00:04:07,700 --> 00:04:09,740
They hung a sign on the door.

76
00:04:09,740 --> 00:04:12,140
Closed.

77
00:04:12,140 --> 00:04:14,160
This is the second twist.

78
00:04:14,160 --> 00:04:18,020
When the Knickerbocker fell, it didn't just scare people in New York.

79
00:04:18,020 --> 00:04:21,940
It triggered a literal financial zombie outbreak.

80
00:04:21,940 --> 00:04:26,860
Because there was no Federal Reserve back then, there was no one to print more money.

81
00:04:26,860 --> 00:04:30,320
If a bank ran out of cash, it died.

82
00:04:30,320 --> 00:04:32,160
Period.

83
00:04:32,160 --> 00:04:33,900
People across America panicked.

84
00:04:33,900 --> 00:04:37,980
They started digging holes in their backyards to bury their cash.

85
00:04:37,980 --> 00:04:39,840
They stopped buying things.

86
00:04:39,840 --> 00:04:41,860
They stopped paying bills.

87
00:04:41,860 --> 00:04:46,860
The gears of the world's largest economy just stopped turning.

88
00:04:46,860 --> 00:04:49,460
The stock exchange began to plummet.

89
00:04:49,460 --> 00:04:52,900
Healthy companies were seeing their value erased in minutes.

90
00:04:52,900 --> 00:04:58,320
By Thursday, the city of New York itself was 48 hours away from being unable to pay its

91
00:04:58,320 --> 00:05:00,280
teachers and firefighters.

92
00:05:00,280 --> 00:05:03,800
The United States was essentially going bankrupt.

93
00:05:03,800 --> 00:05:08,540
Enter the man with the mustache, J.P. Morgan.

94
00:05:08,540 --> 00:05:12,780
At this point, Morgan was 70 years old and semi-retired.

95
00:05:12,780 --> 00:05:16,120
He was at a church convention in Virginia when he got the news.

96
00:05:16,120 --> 00:05:18,780
He didn't wait for a phone call from the President.

97
00:05:18,780 --> 00:05:22,240
He just got on his private train and headed to New York.

98
00:05:22,240 --> 00:05:24,520
Morgan wasn't a nice guy.

99
00:05:24,520 --> 00:05:26,120
He was a predator.

100
00:05:26,120 --> 00:05:30,460
But he realized that if the whole ship sank, his gold sank with it.

101
00:05:30,460 --> 00:05:33,020
When he arrived, he didn't go to the government.

102
00:05:33,020 --> 00:05:38,560
He went to his private library, a massive marble fortress filled with rare books and art.

103
00:05:38,560 --> 00:05:42,520
He sat in his chair, lit a cigar, and waited.

104
00:05:42,520 --> 00:05:44,460
Here is the third twist.

105
00:05:44,460 --> 00:05:49,420
The U.S. Secretary of the Treasury actually traveled to New York to meet Morgan.

106
00:05:49,420 --> 00:05:50,740
Think about that.

107
00:05:50,740 --> 00:05:56,740
The guy in charge of the country's money went to a private citizen's house to ask for help.

108
00:05:56,740 --> 00:06:02,640
The secretary basically admitted, we don't have enough money to stop this.

109
00:06:02,640 --> 00:06:04,720
What do we do?

110
00:06:04,720 --> 00:06:06,680
Morgan's answer was cold.

111
00:06:06,680 --> 00:06:12,280
The government needs to give me their money and I'll decide where it goes.

112
00:06:12,280 --> 00:06:13,600
And they did it.

113
00:06:13,600 --> 00:06:20,480
The U.S. Treasury deposited $25 million, an insane amount of money back then, into banks

114
00:06:20,480 --> 00:06:22,880
that Morgan chose.

115
00:06:22,880 --> 00:06:26,540
Morgan became the temporary king of America.

116
00:06:26,540 --> 00:06:31,640
He sat in his library playing solitaire while the most powerful bankers in the world waited

117
00:06:31,640 --> 00:06:34,360
in the hallway like nervous schoolboys.

118
00:06:34,360 --> 00:06:40,380
He would call them in one by one, look at their books, and decide if they lived or died.

119
00:06:40,380 --> 00:06:43,820
If he thought a bank was run by idiots, he let it fail.

120
00:06:43,820 --> 00:06:46,860
If he thought it was important, he saved it.

121
00:06:46,860 --> 00:06:50,740
But the fire was spreading faster than he could pour water on it.

122
00:06:50,740 --> 00:06:56,180
By Friday, the president of the New York Stock Exchange rushed into Morgan's office.

123
00:06:56,180 --> 00:06:59,480
He told Morgan that the exchange had to close early.

124
00:06:59,480 --> 00:07:05,060
If it stayed open for even another hour, every single broker would go bust.

125
00:07:05,060 --> 00:07:06,540
Morgan looked at his watch.

126
00:07:06,540 --> 00:07:11,760
He told the man, if you close the exchange early, it will cause a panic that will destroy

127
00:07:11,760 --> 00:07:13,080
the world.

128
00:07:13,080 --> 00:07:14,080
Keep it open.

129
00:07:14,080 --> 00:07:17,860
But we have no money, the man cried.

130
00:07:17,860 --> 00:07:19,320
Morgan didn't blink.

131
00:07:19,320 --> 00:07:25,820
He called the heads of the biggest banks and told them they had 10 minutes to raise $25 million.

132
00:07:25,820 --> 00:07:30,720
He told them that if they didn't, he would personally make sure they were ruined.

133
00:07:30,720 --> 00:07:33,100
They found the money in five minutes.

134
00:07:33,100 --> 00:07:35,460
The stock exchange stayed open.

135
00:07:35,460 --> 00:07:38,120
The world survived one more day.

136
00:07:38,120 --> 00:07:40,400
But then came the weekend.

137
00:07:40,400 --> 00:07:43,700
And this is where the story gets legendary.

138
00:07:43,700 --> 00:07:47,760
Morgan realized that Monday morning would bring a new wave of panic.

139
00:07:47,760 --> 00:07:53,080
There was one specific firm, Moore & Schley, that was about to collapse.

140
00:07:53,080 --> 00:07:56,240
If they went down, they would drag the whole market with them.

141
00:07:56,240 --> 00:07:59,260
They needed another $25 million.

142
00:07:59,260 --> 00:08:00,960
But the banks were tired.

143
00:08:00,960 --> 00:08:01,960
They were scared.

144
00:08:01,960 --> 00:08:04,920
They didn't want to lend any more money.

145
00:08:04,920 --> 00:08:11,600
So Morgan invited the 12 most powerful bankers in America to his library for a meeting on Saturday

146
00:08:11,600 --> 00:08:13,100
night.

147
00:08:13,100 --> 00:08:17,040
They walked in, thinking they were there for a chat.

148
00:08:17,040 --> 00:08:19,020
Here is the fourth twist.

149
00:08:19,020 --> 00:08:23,820
As soon as the last banker walked in, Morgan's guards locked the front doors.

150
00:08:23,820 --> 00:08:27,300
They literally locked the bankers inside the building.

151
00:08:27,300 --> 00:08:28,300
Morgan told them,

152
00:08:28,300 --> 00:08:33,160
None of you are leaving this room until we have a plan to save the market.

153
00:08:33,160 --> 00:08:36,340
He then walked into another room to play solitaire.

154
00:08:36,340 --> 00:08:38,160
He let them sit there.

155
00:08:38,160 --> 00:08:39,360
For hours.

156
00:08:39,360 --> 00:08:40,880
He let them argue.

157
00:08:40,880 --> 00:08:42,560
He let them get tired.

158
00:08:42,560 --> 00:08:44,940
He let them get hungry.

159
00:08:44,940 --> 00:08:49,220
At 3 o'clock in the morning, Morgan walked back in with a piece of paper.

160
00:08:49,220 --> 00:08:54,020
It was a contract stating that every bank in the room would chip in to create a massive

161
00:08:54,020 --> 00:08:55,440
rescue fund.

162
00:08:55,440 --> 00:08:58,360
One of the bankers refused to sign.

163
00:08:58,360 --> 00:09:01,620
Morgan walked over to him, put the pen in his hand, and said,

164
00:09:01,620 --> 00:09:05,400
There's the paper, and there's the pen.

165
00:09:05,400 --> 00:09:07,040
Sign it.

166
00:09:07,040 --> 00:09:08,560
The bankers signed.

167
00:09:08,560 --> 00:09:11,280
By 5 a.m., the deal was done.

168
00:09:11,280 --> 00:09:13,040
The doors were unlocked.

169
00:09:13,040 --> 00:09:18,380
The bankers stumbled out into the morning light, having just saved the American economy,

170
00:09:18,380 --> 00:09:21,540
because a 70-year-old man bullied them into it.

171
00:09:21,540 --> 00:09:23,440
But Morgan wasn't done.

172
00:09:23,440 --> 00:09:28,640
He had one more trick up his sleeve, and it's the most controversial part of the story.

173
00:09:28,640 --> 00:09:33,280
While everyone was panicking about the Moore and Schley collapse, Morgan realized he could

174
00:09:33,280 --> 00:09:39,320
solve the problem by having his own company, U.S. Steel, buy a smaller rival company that

175
00:09:39,320 --> 00:09:41,460
Moore and Schley owned.

176
00:09:41,460 --> 00:09:45,800
This would give the firm the cash they needed to survive, but there was a catch.

177
00:09:45,800 --> 00:09:49,960
Buying that company would create a monopoly, which was illegal.

178
00:09:49,960 --> 00:09:53,960
J.P. Morgan needed the president's permission to break the law.

179
00:09:53,960 --> 00:09:56,460
Here is the fifth twist.

180
00:09:56,460 --> 00:10:01,300
Morgan sent a messenger to the White House to see President Teddy Roosevelt.

181
00:10:01,300 --> 00:10:04,720
Roosevelt was famous for being a trust buster.

182
00:10:04,720 --> 00:10:06,460
He hated monopolies.

183
00:10:06,460 --> 00:10:11,920
But Morgan's messenger told him, if you don't let this merger happen, the entire economy will

184
00:10:11,920 --> 00:10:14,300
collapse by noon today.

185
00:10:14,300 --> 00:10:15,460
Roosevelt had a choice.

186
00:10:15,460 --> 00:10:17,960
Uphold the law or save the country.

187
00:10:17,960 --> 00:10:19,800
He chose the country.

188
00:10:19,800 --> 00:10:21,960
He gave Morgan the green light.

189
00:10:21,960 --> 00:10:26,960
Morgan had used a national crisis to legally buy out his biggest competitor and grow even

190
00:10:26,960 --> 00:10:27,960
richer.

191
00:10:27,960 --> 00:10:29,960
To some, he was a hero.

192
00:10:29,960 --> 00:10:34,960
To others, he was a puppet master who had just staged a coup.

193
00:10:34,960 --> 00:10:36,460
The panic ended.

194
00:10:36,460 --> 00:10:38,460
The money returned to the banks.

195
00:10:38,460 --> 00:10:41,460
The mustache king had won.

196
00:10:41,460 --> 00:10:46,460
But this leads us to the final and most important twist of all.

197
00:10:46,460 --> 00:10:49,460
When the dust settled, the American public wasn't grateful.

198
00:10:49,460 --> 00:10:51,300
They were terrified.

199
00:10:51,300 --> 00:10:56,640
They looked at what had happened and realized that the entire United States of America was

200
00:10:56,640 --> 00:10:59,540
basically a one-man show.

201
00:10:59,540 --> 00:11:04,340
If J.P. Morgan had been in a bad mood, or if he had died of a heart attack that weekend,

202
00:11:04,340 --> 00:11:07,100
the country would have ceased to function.

203
00:11:07,100 --> 00:11:11,920
The government realized they could never let a private citizen have that much power again.

204
00:11:11,920 --> 00:11:15,640
They realized that the snack club system was too dangerous.

205
00:11:15,640 --> 00:11:23,140
So three years later, a group of bankers, inspired by the 1907 crisis, snuck off to a place called

206
00:11:23,140 --> 00:11:26,400
Jekyll Island to write a new set of rules.

207
00:11:26,400 --> 00:11:30,740
Those rules became the Federal Reserve Act of 1913.

208
00:11:30,740 --> 00:11:36,340
The Federal Reserve, the giant bank for banks that controls your interest rates and the value

209
00:11:36,340 --> 00:11:41,800
of your dollar today, wasn't created by a bunch of geniuses who wanted to help the poor.

210
00:11:41,800 --> 00:11:46,860
It was created because J.P. Morgan was so good at his job that he scared the government into

211
00:11:46,860 --> 00:11:49,480
replacing him with a machine.

212
00:11:49,480 --> 00:11:54,740
So the next time you look at a dollar bill, remember 1907.

213
00:11:54,740 --> 00:11:59,860
Remember the copper gamble that failed, the bankers locked in a library, and the man with

214
00:11:59,860 --> 00:12:04,480
the mustache who saved America, just so he could own it?

215
00:12:04,480 --> 00:12:08,100
The system we have today wasn't built for stability.

216
00:12:08,100 --> 00:12:13,240
It was built because we realized that depending on one person to save us is the biggest risk

217
00:12:13,240 --> 00:12:13,740
of all.

